03630nam a22006375i 9780814769652DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t19991999nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147696527 a10.18574/nyu/9780814769652.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)550539  a(OCoLC)45733635  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a363.45/09731 aJenkins, Philip, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSynthetic Panics :bThe Symbolic Politics of Designer Drugs /cPhilip Jenkins. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTE ON USAGE -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tONE. Synthetic Panics -- tTWO. Speed Kills -- tTHREE. Monsters -- tFOUR. Suppressing Ecstasy -- tFIVE. The Menace That Went Away -- tSIX. The CAT Attack, 1993–94 -- tSEVEN. Redneck Cocaine -- tEIGHT. Rave Drugs and Rape Drugs -- tNINE. The Next Panic -- tABBREVIATIONS IN NOTES -- tNOTES -- tINDEX -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerica has a long history of drug panics in which countless social problems have been blamed on the devastating effects of some harmful substance. In the last forty years, such panics have often focused on synthetic or designer drugs, like methamphetamine, PCP, Ecstasy, methcathinone, and rave drugs like ketamine, and GHB. Fear of these substances has provided critical justification for the continuing "war on drugs." Synthetic Panics traces the history of these anti-drug movements, demonstrating that designer chemicals inspire so much fear not because they are uniquely dangerous, but because they bring into focus deeply rooted public concerns about social and cultural upheaval. Jenkins highlights the role of the mass media in spreading anti-drug hysteria and shows how proponents of the war on drugs use synthetic panics to scapegoat society's "others" and exacerbate racial, class, and intergenerational conflict.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107169240 cprintz978081474243340uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814769652.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814769652423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814769652/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK